# Behavioral UX Research

## Source Policy
- All major behavioral claims are grounded in publicly available, peer-reviewed, institutional, or official platform documentation.
- Claims about WakeTask-specific implementation details are based on product evidence from this project.
- Any statement not directly traceable to one of the listed sources is labeled as **Inference**.
- No clinical, legal, financial, or psychiatric treatment claims are made.

## Source List
1. **Lally, van Jaarsveld, Potts, & Wardle (2010)**. How are habits formed: Modelling habit formation in the real world. European Journal of Social Psychology, 40, 998-1009. DOI: [10.1002/ejsp.674](https://doi.org/10.1002/ejsp.674).
2. **ISPA repository summary of Lally et al.** includes key design points from that study, including 84-day follow-up, 18–254 day range, and context consistency findings. Source: [ISPA record](https://repositorio.ispa.pt/entities/publication/fae72a1c-b2b6-4991-9951-5d20b607f688).
3. **UCL News release on habit formation study** reporting 66-day average and cue-based automaticity from the above study. Source: [ucl.ac.uk](https://www.ucl.ac.uk/news/2009/aug/how-long-does-it-take-form-habit%20).
4. **Gollwitzer & Sheeran (2006)**. Implementation Intentions and Goal Achievement: A Meta-analysis of Effects and Processes. Advances in Experimental Social Psychology, 38, 69–119. DOI: [10.1016/S0065-2601(06)38002-1](https://doi.org/10.1016/S0065-2601(06)38002-1).
5. **Webb, Webb, & Sheeran (2006)**. Does changing behavioral intentions engender behavior change? Psychological Bulletin, 132(2), 249-268. DOI: [10.1037/0033-2909.132.2.249](https://doi.org/10.1037/0033-2909.132.2.249).
6. **Ogawa, Kaizuma-Ueyama, & Hayashi (2022)**. Effects of using a snooze alarm on sleep inertia after morning awakening. Journal of Physiological Anthropology. Source PDF: [jphysiolanthropol...00317-w.pdf](https://jphysiolanthropol.biomedcentral.com/counter/pdf/10.1186/s40101-022-00317-w.pdf).
7. **Ryan & Deci (2000)**. Self-Determination Theory and the facilitation of intrinsic motivation, social development, and well-being. PDF: [2000_RyanDeci_SDT.pdf](https://www.selfdeterminationtheory.org/SDT/documents/2000_RyanDeci_SDT.pdf).
8. **Apple App Review Guidelines**. iOS distribution and behavior constraints (including repeated manipulative behavior, privacy, data-use trust and guideline 5.1 / 5.3 references). Source: [Apple Developer App Review Guidelines](https://developer.apple.com/app-store/review/guidelines/).
9. **Apple Support**. Notification controls and scheduling summary options. Source: [Change notification settings on iPhone](https://support.apple.com/guide/iphone/change-notification-settings-iph7c3d96bab/ios).
10. **Apple Human Interface Guidelines**. Notification management and permission/opt-in considerations. Source: [Apple Human Interface Guidelines – Managing Notifications](https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/managing-notifications).
11. **Bhattacharya, Garber, & Goldhaber-Fiebert (2015)**. Nudges in Exercise Commitment Contracts: A Randomized Trial. NBER Working Paper w21406. DOI: [10.3386/w21406](https://www.nber.org/papers/w21406).
12. **Product evidence**. Current WakeTask app screen inventory and flow captured in stage outputs and existing repo structure (screen names such as onboarding, home, primary_list, create_edit, active_task, completion, history_streaks, profile_settings, paywall_subscription).

## User Motivation Constraints
- Wake-task users face a classic intention-action gap: motivation alone does not reliably predict action; stronger intentions produce only a modest behavioral effect. This creates a need for action-specific support and reminders. (Source: Webb, Webb, & Sheeran, 2006).
- Habits in daily behavior are variable in build time; the cited habit study reports a typical pattern around two months with high individual variance and non-linear growth. (Source: Lally et al. 2010; UCL summary).
- Missing a single opportunity does not necessarily destroy habit progression, so forcing perfect consistency can over-penalize users. (Source: Lally et al. summary in ISPA record).
- Sleep inertia and waking-state transitions can reduce cognitive clarity in the first minutes after waking, so motivation cues in the first post-alarm moments face reduced processing capacity and higher error risk. (Source: Ogawa et al. 2022).
- Inference: product value for this category is strongest when the system reduces required decision complexity at wake time while preserving user control in calm setup phases.

## Friction And Commitment Patterns
- Reliable long-horizon behavior requires low-friction repetition, stable cues, and reduced decision burden in daily execution flow. (Source: Lally et al. 2010; UCL summary).
- If-then planning is useful because intention-to-behavior translation benefits from pre-specifying when/where/how a target action should occur; implementation intentions showed medium-to-large effects in the reviewed evidence. (Source: Gollwitzer & Sheeran, 2006).
- Repeated interruption at wake time compounds friction by adding cognitive load when users are likely groggy; this argues for defaults that work without fine-grained setup choices while waking. (Source: Ogawa et al. 2022).
- Commitment mechanisms should not assume linear adherence across all users and all weeks; engagement often decays or varies over time. (Source: Lally et al. 2010).
- Inference: for this product, short commitments + periodic reset affordances are likely safer than irreversible long commitments.

## Reward And Accountability Patterns
- External rewards and penalties can aid first use, but behavior science indicates stronger outcomes come from structures that bridge motivation into action (implementation-style planning) rather than only intention reinforcement. (Source: Gollwitzer & Sheeran, 2006; Webb et al., 2006).
- Commitment contracts can improve follow-through when users are nudged toward clear commitments, but behavioral-economic evidence also notes welfare tradeoffs when stakes are overextended. (Source: Bhattacharya et al., 2015).
- For sustained adherence, social/competence-supportive feedback is often more durable than shame/penalty-only systems, especially because unmet goals are common and not always due to low motivation. (Source: Lally et al.; Ryan & Deci SDT framework).
- Inference: use reinforcement that increases perceived competence and voluntary ownership, not coercive dependency on failure-based pressure.

## Risk And Harm Avoidance
- Urgent wake behavior should avoid high-friction gamified pressure and avoid escalating repeated snooze patterns, as the snooze study indicates repeated forced wake-sleep transitions can prolong performance degradation after waking. (Source: Ogawa et al. 2022).
- Product-level safeguards are required where users may feel pressured or deceived during account and in-app purchase flows; Apple’s platform guidance explicitly disallows manipulative conduct and preying on users. (Source: Apple App Review Guidelines).
- Notification timing and controls can become a harm vector if they increase sleep disruption or anxiety; iOS design guidance and Apple support indicate users can and should control alert frequency and per-app delivery settings. (Source: Apple HIG summary; Apple Support).
- Inference: avoid auto-escalating notification cadence without explicit user preference, and avoid content that induces panic-based urgency outside immediate safety context.

## Screen Type Implications
- **Calm setup screens (Onboarding, Create/Edit, Profile/Settings):** optimized for deliberation, explanation, and personalization. Evidence and constraints favor richer choice here because users are not yet in aroused wake state. (Inference supported by sleep inertia research on reduced morning cognitive control).
- **Daily-use core screens (Home, Primary List, Active Task):** should privilege minimal choices, high scanability, and one-tap continuation.
- **Completion screen:** should close loops quickly with a clear outcome signal and optional next-step recommendation to reduce decision fatigue after an urgent action.
- **History/Streaks:** can support commitment and identity, but avoid punitive visual language that frames misses as failures; SDT-compatible framing supports competence/autonomy instead. (Source: Ryan & Deci SDT + habit variation data).
- **Paywall/Subscription:** must be explicit, non-deceptive, and optional, because platform policy explicitly penalizes manipulative discovery/consent behavior and app-store trust violations. (Source: Apple App Review Guidelines).
- **Calm setup vs urgent wake distinction:** calm screens should support planning and permission setup, while wake/activation screens should stay action-first, with optional “defer” or “snooze” paths that do not fragment next steps or encourage repeated alarm loops.

## what_to_adapt
- Build an **if-then wake plan** pattern for reminders/actions (e.g., “when alarm is dismissed, show task confirmation with one primary action”). (Source: Gollwitzer & Sheeran, 2006).
- Design habit-forming repetition loops around stable contexts and low-friction recurring flow so missing one slot does not reset progress. (Source: Lally et al. 2010).
- Use staged commitments: shorter trial commitment windows with optional extension, with easy pause/restart rather than punitive lockouts. (Source: Bhattacharya et al., 2015).
- Use notification controls that respect user preferences (scheduled summary, per-app settings, opt-in clarity), while still allowing urgent wake alerts by default. (Source: Apple Support, Apple HIG).
- Replace control-heavy framing with autonomy-supportive framing (choice, customization, clear rationale) to sustain behavior quality over time. (Source: Ryan & Deci, 2000).
- On onboarding, keep permission requests contextual and purposeful; avoid immediate, dense modal cascades during high-anxiety moments. (Source: Apple notification guidance; Apple Support).

## what_not_to_copy
- Do not build fake urgency loops or deceptive progress messaging that pressures users into in-app actions (manipulative marketing patterns are disallowed by platform guidance). (Source: Apple App Review Guidelines).
- Do not require strict streaks to continue app usage or remove core functionality as punishment after misses; evidence shows imperfect consistency is normal and habit development is non-linear. (Source: Lally et al. 2010).
- Do not optimize for repeated snooze/reward cycles that can increase sleep inertia and reduce immediate post-awakening clarity. (Source: Ogawa et al. 2022).
- Do not default to broad push notification spamming; expose granular controls and schedule options to reduce interruption burden. (Source: Apple Support).
- Avoid excessive social comparison that uses shame, public ranking without consent, or coercive accountability. This is an inference from safety, autonomy, and coercion-risk constraints in this category and platform trust expectations.
