# Behavioral UX Research

## Source Policy
- Claims below are grounded in peer-reviewed behavioral science, established human-interface documentation, and app-platform policy. Sources are in [Source List](#source-list).
- Where the evidence is incomplete for a specific product decision, claims are marked as **Inference**.
- This document avoids medical, legal, or psychological diagnosis claims; it focuses on product behavior design constraints.
- Sensitive implementation notes are treated as behavioral design principles only and do not alter medical care guidance.

## Source List
1. **Lally et al. (2010)** – Habits were modeled over 84 days in real-world contexts; median time to 95% automaticity was 66 days (range 18–254) and missing opportunities was not a major blocker for habit formation.
   - Source: https://www.flexyourbrain.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/10/UL-STUDY-66-Days-IJSP_998-1009.pdf
2. **Gollwitzer & Sheeran (2006) / implementation intentions meta-analysis** – Holds that implementation intentions (“if-then” plans) improve goal attainment versus intention alone (medium-to-large effect), by shielding goal pursuit from self-regulation failures.
   - Source: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/chapter/bookseries/abs/pii/S0065260106380021
3. **How can implementation intentions effects be improved? (Prestwich & Kellar, 2014)** – Summarizes moderators: collaboration/plan reminders/goal type; intention strength matters most frequently.
   - Source: https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/abs/pii/S1162908810000186
4. **Nudges in Exercise Commitment Contracts (Bhattacharya et al., 2015)** – People nudged toward longer commitment contracts chose longer contracts and met goals more; longer commitments can improve follow-through behavior.
   - Source: https://www.nber.org/papers/w21406
5. **Ogawa et al. (2022)** – Snooze use in alarms reduced anxiety about oversleeping for many users but was associated with longer sleep inertia and fragmented sleep in the final pre-wake period.
   - Source: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40101-022-00317-w
6. **Alarms and sleep inertia review (2020, systematic review)** – Highlights that alarm characteristics (voice/melodic/low-frequency variants) can influence post-awakening sleep inertia differently.
   - Source: https://www.mdpi.com/2624-5175/2/4/31
7. **Sleep inertia study context** – Sleep inertia is reduced alertness and performance impairment around awakening.
   - Source: https://link.springer.com/article/10.1186/s40101-022-00317-w
8. **Apple Notification Best Practices (HIG / docs)** – Avoid unnecessary repeated notifications; requests should not overload users and should provide concise value.
   - Source: https://developer.apple.com/design/human-interface-guidelines/notifications
9. **Apple Local & Remote Notification Support Guide** – Authorization is user-controlled; request at app launch for capabilities (alerts, sounds, badges), and notifications should remain user-governed.
   - Source: https://developer.apple.com/library/archive/documentation/NetworkingInternet/Conceptual/RemoteNotificationsPG/SupportingNotificationsinYourApp.html
10. **Apple App Store Guidelines** – Prohibits using notifications for spam/unwanted marketing, prohibits spamming/disguised behavior, and disallows predatory/manipulative app practices.
   - Source: https://developer.apple.com/app-store/review/guidelines/
11. **Loss aversion reference point model (Kahneman et al.)** – People weight losses more than equivalent gains.
   - Source: https://academic.oup.com/qje/article-pdf/106/4/1039/5298142/106-4-1039.pdf
12. **Fogg Behavior Model (framework source)** – Behavior when motivation, ability, and prompt converge (design lens for wake/setup moments).
   - Source: https://www.behaviormodel.org/
13. **Self-Determination Theory** – Motivation quality rises when autonomy/competence/relatedness are supported.
   - Source: https://selfdeterminationtheory.org/the-theory/

## User Motivation Constraints
- Wake behavior is situationally constrained by physiological state rather than pure intention: users often wake with reduced cognitive performance and sleep inertia immediately after awakening, making complex choices harder and increasing error risk. [Source: Ogawa et al. 2022]
- Stronger wake-state anxiety is common in this product domain: in one mobile sample, most users used snooze in part to reduce anxiety about oversleeping, even when sleep quality impacts were modest. [Source: Ogawa et al. 2022]
